    <item>
      <title>Coupling Algorithms in the EC-Earth AOSCM</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/project/scm_coupling/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 15 Jun 2023 16:47:47 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/project/scm_coupling/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I started working with the EC-Earth coupled atmosphere–ocean single-column model (&lt;a href=&#34;https://doi.org/10.5194/gmd-11-4117-2018&#34;&gt;Hartung et al., 2018&lt;/a&gt;) during my &lt;a href=&#34;http://localhost:1313/publication/msc-thesis/&#34;&gt;master&amp;rsquo;s thesis&lt;/a&gt;.
This is a version of the &lt;a href=&#34;https://ec-earth.org/&#34;&gt;EC-Earth global climate model&lt;/a&gt; which is useful for model development, particularly regarding physics parameterizations in the atmospheric and oceanic boundary layers.
In my work, I have created scripts and workflows to study the impact of different coupling algorithms on model output.
My master&amp;rsquo;s thesis covers pure atmosphere-ocean coupling, we are working to include other models as well (e.g., the sea ice model &lt;a href=&#34;https://doi.org/10.5194/gmd-8-2991-2015&#34;&gt;LIM3&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The goal here is to make the EC-Earth AOSCM a tool for coupling algorithm development in climate models.
See the &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/valentinaschueller/ece-scm-coupling&#34;&gt;corresponding GitHub repository&lt;/a&gt; for further information.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Collaborators:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.maths.lu.se/staff/philipp-birken&#34;&gt;Philipp Birken&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a href=&#34;https://membres-ljk.imag.fr/Florian.Lemarie/&#34;&gt;Florian Lemarié&lt;/a&gt; &amp;amp; &lt;a href=&#34;https://membres-ljk.imag.fr/Eric.Blayo/&#34;&gt;Eric Blayo&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;a href=&#34;https://team.inria.fr/airsea/en/&#34;&gt;AIRSEA Group&lt;/a&gt;, INRIA Grenoble); &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.su.se/english/research/research-groups/dynamic-meteorology&#34;&gt;Dynamic Meteorology Group at MISU&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
